body: this feature is only active if $TOX_LOG_KEYS is set at runtime and tox has been compiled in debug mode and it will work together with https://github.com/cleverca22/tox_decoder or other similar tools to allow decrypting packets for debug --- This change is [](https://reviewable.io/reviews/toktok/c-toxcore/268)

--- Reviewed 2 of 3 files at r1, 1 of 1 files at r2. Review status: all files reviewed at latest revision, all discussions resolved. --- _Comments from [Reviewable](https://reviewable.io:443/reviews/toktok/c-toxcore/268#-:-KWTCe8s46ybBduN6NTm:b-jbsf8z)_

I'm not happy with:
- (Unguarded) global key output stream. What will happen if you run two toxes in parallel (looks like some non-deterministic mix of hex number output will happen, or perhaps it works, depending on the implementation's IO buffer size)?
- (Re-)introducing stdio into toxcore (ok, it's guarded behind `TOX_DEBUG`, but I'm also against `TOX_DEBUG`).
- Configuring behaviour through env vars.

I understand this is debug code, but how about an alternative solution: introducing debug callbacks. This could go in the same direction as the log callback, in that it would be initialised through `Tox_Options`. There are various internal processes that might be interesting to have debug callbacks for:
- Logging (already done).
- Key generation to enable external real-time traffic analysers to decrypt and decode packets.
- Packet sending (what kind, to whom, what size, etc.) to enable simpler protocol accounting and gathering of statistics.
- Hole punching status (started, trying to hole punch, success).

What do you think?

---

_Comments from [Reviewable](https://reviewable.io:443/reviews/toktok/c-toxcore/268#-:-KWd9WoxW4Ru4DlR-UDV:bsjy237)_

<!-- Sent from Reviewable.io -->

my main issue with using the logging callbacks, is that the client now needs to know what format to write to the log file, so the wireshark plugin can understand it

and even if you do trick a user into `export TOX_KEY_DIR`, he must already have a debug build of toxcore, and normal users shouldn't be running one

If you use a debugging callback, instead of writing to file, you could set up a piece of shared protected memory with whatever tool you're using for debugging, and avoid writing keys to permanent storage. You give the client more freedom to implement debugging facilities more easily.

shm would be nice and improve some of the problems of new keys being made after the file was loaded

but it would also get in the way of being able to save the keys and .pcap to disk to analyze at a later date

@iphydf what else do you think i could use, other then TOX_LOG_KEYS

the only thing i can think of that would prevent keys from going to the hdd, while still allowing a developer to choose such a security risk would be to hard-code it to /dev/shm/tox-keys, but then how do you turn it on/off?

it is now possible to log all of the required keys via LD_PRELOAD: https://github.com/cleverca22/tox_decoder/commit/443172ef48a7be7ac8cf87b04becb7e1df22a123

no longer need to modify toxcore to make things work

commit.message:
allow exporting keypairs in debug build

this feature is only active if $TOX_LOG_KEYS is set at runtime and tox has been compiled in debug mode
